crutiny. Also there is a very small number of the species that make up the human microbiome that can be cultured outside of the human GI tract. A healthy diet is likely a better solution, unless of course &quot;Joe&quot; has a medical condition such as IBD and can find a Doctor willing to perform a fecal transplant."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8234e4694103058c72b14c86d40bec45?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20658,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20658/jonny","reputation":6,"display_name":"Jonny"},"score":0,"post_id":41554,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450229692,"comment_id":70539,"body":"@AMR With &quot;<i>Also there is a very small number of the species that make up the human microbiome that can be cultured outside of the human GI tract.<\/i>&quot; did you try to imply that it is <b>impossible<\/b> to make pro-biotic supplements in the first place, because most species of good-bacteria would die right away once packed in pro-biotic capsules? I.E. suggesting that pro-biotic suppelement claims for that kind of bacteria would be scam? Is there somewhere a catalog of bacteria that would identify these kind of bacteria that can&#39;t be transferred via capsules?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":1,"post_id":41554,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450233151,"comment_id":70543,"body":"&quot;Studies of Segmented Filamentous Bacteria biology have been hampered by the current absence of ex-vivo culture methods.&quot; -Ivanov II, Littman DR. Segmented filamentous bacteria take the stage. Mucosal Immuno