http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13338/eli-korvigo","reputation":548,"display_name":"Eli Korvigo","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":41554,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450291235,"comment_id":70586,"body":"Statistics-wise the sample size is too ridiculous to call this an experiment, because you can&#39;t control any random effects if your sample consists of a single person."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/986656e4512511a0c55dc91dd218bbeb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18905,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18905/nathan","reputation":1086,"display_name":"Nathan"},"score":0,"post_id":41554,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450292495,"comment_id":70587,"body":"I agree with Eli, unless you have a lab and a moderate amount of microbiological training/skill, you&#39;re not going to know the answer to any of those questions.  When it fails, you&#39;d have no way of knowing where."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41554/is-it-worth-to-experiment-with-pro-biotics-at-home","last_activity_date":1450228070,"creation_date":1450223149,"answer_count":0,"title":"Is it worth to experiment with pro-biotics at home?","body":"<p>Let's assume that Joe has done some investigation on Internet and wants to see, if pro-biotics would help him. Now he goes to amazon.com and buys a pro-biotic product with excellent average rating. Note that not all of the reviews are from  \"Amazon Verified Purchaser\" for the specific product, but you got the point that it sound convincing that other people claim to benefit from the product.<\/p>\n\n<p>So validity of Joe's pro-biotic experiment starts from pro-biotic supply chain. <strong>What are the steps in his pro-biotic experiment where experiment could go wrong; and what are the precautions he can take to make his experiment successful - either prove or disprove their benefits?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>In the answer I seek something between lines (feel free to reuse these points to make your answer whole):<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <ol>\n  <li>Joe should be confident that seller is selling the real thing and not  candies. <em>Are there any regulations that ensure that there is no fraud going on at this step from Over-the-Counter seller? How common is such fraud by sellers? Have there been any studies?<\/em><\/li>\n  <li>The bacteria might die during shipping before Joe actually received his pro-biotics, for example, because of temperature changes. <em>Obviously responsible seller should know how his merchandise should be shipped.<\/em><\/li>\n  <li>Joe should probably not take pro-biotics together with other drugs or even together with other pro-biotics, because they might kill each other.<\/li>\n  <li>There already could be some bacteria living in Joe's body that immediately kills \"good bacteria\" in pro-biotics without even making it.<\/li>\n  <li>And most important - The initial hypothesis found by Joe on Internet about \"good bacteria\" in pro-biotics was wrong in the first place. <em>Is there a website that I can check with convincing research that has studied how each bacteria affects our body as a whole?<\/em><\/li>\n  <\/ol>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Also, would it be worth to grow culture of pro-biotics at home to make sure that there is bacteria in the first place? How hard that would be? We have microscope at home.<\/p>\n\n<p><em>The reason I am asking this is because a person very close to me is super excited about pro-biotics so that it starts to affect my life. I just want to get opinion from people in the biology field on how skeptical they are about DIY people doing such pro-biotic experiments at home. I am not sure yet whether I should support this person or try to talk out of this. It seems that this person has been reading a lot on Internet about this subject so it is not easy for me to argue back.<\/em><\/p>\n","question_id":41554,"tags":["bacteriology","health","experimental","microbiome"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":37,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1450228070},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4494dce93121582cc775a9672fe382da?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20575,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20575/louis-somers","reputation":118,"display_name":"Louis Somers"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":41415,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449788055,"comment_id":70251,"body":"Welcome to Biology.SE. Is your question &quot;How come our gut <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endosymbiont\" rel=\"nofollow\">endosymbionts<\/a> don&#39;t get killed by our immune system?&quot; or is it &quot;Are gut endosymbionts inherited from the mother or are they acquired by the baby through food?&quot;"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":0,"post_id":41415,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449788722,"comment_id":70253,"body":"I think he&#39;s asking &quot;Where does the gut microbiotia start from?&quot;"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4494dce93121582cc775a9672fe382da?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20575,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20575/louis-somers","reputation":118,"display_name":"Louis Somers"},"score":1,"post_id":41415,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2442ea911c89187262d6575d739a1ca7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5148,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5148/s