biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":41514,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450084044,"comment_id":70432,"body":"Sure. In fact all chemical reactions are essentially stochastic. I would however interpret &quot;random primers&quot; as set of <b>n<\/b> primers generated using a random number toss for a nucleotide at each position for all <b>n<\/b> primers. At <b>n→∞<\/b> all possible permutations can be obtained."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":41514,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450104447,"comment_id":70446,"body":"For practical purposes, IDT offers randomized oligos. Saves a lot of trouble.Other companies probably offer this too."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41514,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450159793,"comment_id":70478,"body":"As far I know, the way that Mad Scientist describes it is how random oligos are generated. There may be more advanced methods that the synthetic DNA providers like IDT use these days, but in principle that was how it was done around the time of the publication date of the paper."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":41514,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450193800,"comment_id":70507,"body":"@AMR Fundamentally it&#39;s the same chemistry, but IDT has it very well optimized, at the chemistry and synthesizer level. I&#39;ve seen their plant a couple times and it&#39;s amazing how they can turn out so many oligos in a day from some nondescript building next to the walmart. Their shipping department is probably the best nonviral DNA delivery group in the world."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450082313,"creation_date":1450082313,"body":"<p>If you want to synthesize a specific DNA sequence chemically, you start by attaching your first nucleotide (one letter in your DNA) to a solid phase. You can then continue adding individual letters to it. Because it is bound to a solid support material, you can wash the whole thing without washing your growing DNA away.<\/p>\n\n<p>So if you want to synthesize AGC, you would first only add A to your reaction and then wash away all the A that hasn't reacted. Then you'd add G, which binds to your previous A, and again wash away all the G that hasn't reacted. Then you'd add C, and do the whole thing again.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you want to create a random or semi-random sequence, you simply add multiple letters at once. If you always add all four letters in each step, you'll get a completely random sequence. You can also randomize only specific positions, and only there add all letters.<\/p>\n\n<p>The result is random, but I don't think it is as random as e.g. a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator. There are various factors that can affect the randomness, variations in the concentrations of your nucleotides, variations in the quality or composition of your reactants and probably a lot more.  <\/p>\n\n<p>See also <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligonucleotide_synthesis\" rel=\"nofollow\">Oligonucleotide synthesis on Wikipedia<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":41514,"question_id":41513,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41513/how-can-i-generate-a-random-dna-sequence","last_activity_date":1450128798,"creation_date":1450081167,"answer_count":1,"title":"How can I generate a random DNA sequence?","body":"<p>I've found <a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/83/19/7405.full.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">this paper<\/a> which involves the construction of 19-bp random DNA sequences, but I don't know enough biology to understand how this method works.  Could someone explain it to someone who is highly technical, but has knowledge of only introductory, undergraduate biology?  How do the authors know that their resultant sequence is truly random?  <\/p>\n","question_id":41513,"tags":["dna","dna-sequencing","sequence-analysis"],"score":7,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":90,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1450128798},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5b5440c34109e218b55c29d2450159ee?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6136/21joanna12","reputation":659,"display_name":"21joanna12","accept_rate":46},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/56b4833d86d3cccc3ccfd6eeaf0b767e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14946,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14946/mdperry","reputation":2645,"display_name":"mdperry"},"score":0,"post_id":40963,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448412427,"comment_id":69265,"body":"I agree that one could read the passage and conclude that the authors are referring to the same &quot; deletion in chromosome 15&quot; but as @yingw explains in Prader-Willi Syndrome it is one region of Chr 15 and in Angelman Syndrome it is a different region of Chr 15."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ebb68d88984f244afbfb056ed5a77e47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":766,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/766/yingw","reputation":641,"display_name":"yingw"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1448404923,"creation_date":1448404923,"body":"<p>Within that region, there are multiple genes.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Although the same gene may control imprinting for both disorders, the\n  gene(s) causing their phenotypes differ. AS results from\n  underexpression of a single gene, UBE3A, which codes for E6-AP, a\n  protein that functions to transfer small ubiquitin molecules to\n  certain target proteins, to enable their degradation. The genes\n  responsible for PWS are not determined, although several maternally\n  imprinted genes in 15q11-q13 are known. The most likely candidate is\n  SNRPN<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>From this paper: <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11180221\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11180221<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":40968,"question_id":40963,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450115588,"creation_date":1448418957,"body":"<p>In a wild-type human, you will inherit one paternal chromosome and one maternal chromosome, in this case, chromosome 15.<\/p>\n\n<p>The paternal chromosome which is packaged into the sperm will be methylated in such a way that the <a href=\"http://omim.org/entry/601623\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ubiqitin-Protein Ligase E3A<\/a> (<em>UBE3A<\/em>) gene is silenced.<\/p>\n\n<p>The maternal chromosome which is packaged into the oocyte will be methylated in such a way that the <a href=\"http://omim.org/entry/182279\" rel=\"nofollow\">Small Nuclear Ribonucleoprotein Polypeptide N<\/a> (<em>SNRPN<\/em>) and <a href=\"http://omim.org/entry/602117\" rel=\"nofollow\">NECDIN<\/a> (<em>NDN<\/em>) genes are silenced.<\/p>\n\n<p>When the egg is fertilized, it has the paternal chromosome and the maternal chromosome, which <strong>complement<\/strong> each other (The same as a genetic complementation test would). <\/p>\n\n<p>In a wild-time embryo, <em>UBE3A<\/em> is expressed off of the maternal chromosome, and <em>SNRPN<\/em> and <em>NDN<\/em> will be expressed from the paternal chromosome, and the wild-type phenotype will be rescued.<\/p>\n\n<p>So in <a href=\"http://omim.org/entry/176270\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>Prader-Willi Syndrome<\/strong><\/a>, at some point in time, the DNA that went into the male gamete sustained a deletion at 15q11, so the entire locus, with those three genes was lost. If that sperm then fertilizes an egg, the paternal chromosome no longer has <em>SNRPN<\/em> and <em>NDN<\/em> to rescue the wild-type phenotype. Because those genes are silenced on the maternal chromosome and deleted on the paternal chromosome, there is no allele available to express the relevant gene product. In effect, this embryo will be the equivalent of <em>null/null<\/em> for <em>SNRPN<\/em> and <em>NDN<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Then in <a href=\"http://omim.org/entry/105830\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>Angelman Syndrome<\/strong><\/a>, the opposite situation is in effect. The DNA that went into the female gamete sustained a deletion at 15q11, so the entire locus, with those three genes was lost. If that egg is fertilized, then the maternal chromosome will not be available to rescue the wild-type phenotype because the <em>UBE3A<\/em> is silenced on the paternal chromosome. In effect, this embryo will be the equivalent of <em>null/null<\/em> for <em>UBE3A<\/em><\/p>\n\n<p>So in effect Prader-Willi Syndrome is the phenotype for the <em>SNRPN<\/em> and <em>NDN<\/em> <em>null/null<\/em> mutant and Angelman Syndrome is the phenotype for the <em>UBE3A<\/em> <em>null/null<\/em> mutant.<\/p>\n\n<p>Even though the genes are present on one of the alleles, the sex determined imprinting causes different genes to be silence, so that is why the same deletion is able to produce two different phenotypes, depending on which gamete that forms the embryo sustains the deletion.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40976,"question_id":40963,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1450115588}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40963/prader-willi-syndrome-and-angelman-syndrome","last_activity_date":1450115588,"creation_date":1448398810,"answer_count":2,"title":"Prader-Willi Syndrome and Angelman Syndrome?","body":"<p>On the website <a href=\"http://www.whatisepigenetics.com/fundamentals/2/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.whatisepigenetics.com/fundamentals/2/<\/a> it states that <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>the imprint disorders Prader-Willi syndrome and Angelman syndrome, display an abnormal phenotype as a result of the absence of the paternal or maternal copy of a gene, respectively. In these imprint disorders, there is a genetic deletion in chromosome 15 in a majority of patients. The same gene on the corresponding chromosome cannot compensate for the deletion because it has been turned off by methylation, an epigenetic modification.  Genetic deletions inherited from the father result in Prader-Willi syndrome, and those inherited from the mother, Angelman syndrome.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>To me it seems like this is suggesting the same problem in both Prader-Willi and Angelman sydrome- lack of expression of a particular gene. However in Prader-Willi syndrome it is the paternal chromosome that is missing and the maternal copy of this gene is silenced by methylation and the reverse applies for Angelman syndrome. Therefore it seems that in boh cases the problem is the lack of expression of this gene. Why, then, if both are caused by lack of expression of this gene, do these two illnesses have such different symptoms (constant hunger in Prader-Willi syndrome and mental disability and jerky movements in Angelman syndrome)? <\/p>\n","question_id":40963,"tags":["dna","human-genetics","epigenetics"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":40976,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":69,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2f00e7c2fdb2edd7026c9a5e9a642fcf?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":10333,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10333/start","reputation":6,"display_name":"start"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"score":1,"post_id":24287,"edited":false,"creation_date":1416855192,"comment_id":38789,"body":"What kind of research are you thinking about? You might find the magnification/resolution of a bright field microscope limiting."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f9bd7c0a93e1587d390866d374842b91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9829,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9829/luigi","reputation":2475,"display_name":"Luigi"},"score":1,"post_id":24287,"edited":false,"creation_date":1416861231,"comment_id":38792,"body":"It doesn&#39;t matter whether you&#39;re using your microscope in a 2 billion dollar building or a garden shed, a microscope is a microscope. Either way you&#39;ll want a clean work area, isolated from the rest of your living space (especially depending on what you plan to stain with). You&#39;ll get out what you put in. Is the opportunity worth $2300 USD <b>to you<\/b>?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/40ac74fd3b7a35cb98d0660d74098dfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20631,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20631/ch-zymler","reputation":1,"display_name":"Ch Zymler"},"score":0,"post_