al for odd number of limbs or asymmetric division. That&#39;s clearly not why bilateral symmetry occurs."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f2a6c0c8832e2bc9a1b784c2117ae4f5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8337,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8337/user31782","reputation":313,"display_name":"user31782"},"score":0,"post_id":39231,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"edited":false,"creation_date":1444205921,"comment_id":65867,"body":"@GoodGravy I could not understand your comment. &quot;<i>6 cells, or any other even multiple of an odd number of cells<\/i>&quot; So what 2N will always be even whatever N you choose."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":39231,"edited":false,"creation_date":1444211262,"comment_id":65872,"body":"@user31782 Asymmetric expansion can occur due to directional growth from an odd number of nodes (even if the cell count remains even). But here&#39;s the kicker of why that argument is broken; it is taking a cellular principle and making a lot of assumptions about it (constant cell cycle period, uniform cell death etc)  and oversimplifying it (for example it ignores inter-cellular communication and genetic control systems), and then applies that watered down concept at a complex multi-tissue organism scale involving not millions, nor billions, but tens of trillions of cells."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1nMw6.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1