n it is eating. When standing it uses its tail like the third leg of a tripod. When it is running only its hind legs touch the ground, both together, using its tail for balance with its front legs dangling high off the ground. So when running it&#39;s using an either one or two legged gait, depending whether you consider two legs in unison to be one or two. Even when eating it moves its legs in pairs instead of individually. So although it has four limbs and a tail it uses them as two limbs and a tail, but with extra lateral stability."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a51980d404d08ba2b8c640ce12120c88?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17617,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17617/bshane","reputation":1739,"display_name":"bshane"},"score":0,"post_id":39234,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0fc20bdaa2bbda327e40790844dafdd3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10204,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10204/cj-dennis","reputation":206,"display_name":"CJ Dennis"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1443956773,"comment_id":65673,"body":"@CJDennis: It&#39;s not true that kangaroos only use their tail as &#39;the third leg of a tripod&#39;. In the study I linked to, the authors defined the kangaroo&#39;s tail as functionally a leg because the tail provided forward propulsion in the animal&#39;s five-legged gait. In fact, while walking on five legs, the tail provided as much forward propulsion as both the front legs and hind (should I say middle?) legs combined."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0fc20bdaa2bbda327e40790844dafdd3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10204,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10204/cj-dennis","reputation":206,"display_name":"CJ Dennis"},"score":0,"post_id":39234,"edited":false,"creation_date":1443956943,"comment_id":65674,"body":"I did say &quot;when standing&quo