user_type":"registered","user_id":17617,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17617/bshane","reputation":1739,"display_name":"bshane"},"score":0,"post_id":39234,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f2a6c0c8832e2bc9a1b784c2117ae4f5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8337,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8337/user31782","reputation":313,"display_name":"user31782"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1444021602,"comment_id":65712,"body":"@user31782: It sounds like your definition of &#39;leg&#39; is by structure. I would argue that it is not a useful definition of &#39;leg&#39; for evolutionary questions. e.g., the hindlegs of horses are not &#39;two long bones with a hand-like structure at the end&#39;, because there are three long bones (the bones that are homologous with the arch of our feet are fused into a third long bone, IIRC). But they are definitely &#39;legs&#39; in the way most people understand the term! Biologists avoid semantic problems by defining from homology - in which case, see the second part of my answer re: development and asymmetry."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4690b9a0df8a4c1e35c088b077942e6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6132,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6132/steve-jessop","reputation":320,"display_name":"Steve Jessop"},"score":0,"post_id":39234,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f2a6c0c8832e2bc9a1b784c2117ae4f5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8337,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8337/user31782","reputation":313,"display_name":"user31782"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1444039174,"comment_id":65727,"body":"@user31782: if you&#39;re defining legs in terms of &quot;bones&quot;, then you&#39;re talking about vertebrates, not all animals. Which is a fair enough thing to ask about, but this restriction means that straight away, all terrestrial vertebrates are tetrapods, who all (including kangaroos) have inherited a basic body plan with bilateral symmetry from a common (fish) ancestor. The success of this body plan has yet to be challenged by any odd-limbed species, other than those using their tail as a limb. Depending on your view of &quot;arms&quot; and vestigial limbs, they all have 0, 2 or 4 &quot;legs&quot;."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1444022630,"creation_date":1443867544,"body":"<p>It depends what you mean by 'leg'.<\/p>\n\n<p>The instinctive way to define a 'leg' is based on its functional use: we use legs to walk on. But if we adopt that definition of 'leg' then there certainly are animals with odd numbers of legs: kangaroos, for instance, have a five-legged gait, functionally <a href=\"http://news.sciencemag.org/biology/2014/07/amazing-five-legged-kangaroo\" rel=\"nofollow\">using their tail as a fifth leg<\/a>. There is no developmental process that stops an animal from growing an odd number of <em>appendages<\/em>, and if one of those appendages happens to be used as a leg, evolution and development will have no problem with that.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, there is another way to define 'leg', and that is by homology - 'legs' are the appendages derived by evolution from the legs of a common ancestor. Under this definition, (for vertebrates, at least) you're a bit more hard-pressed to find examples of animals with an odd number. This is because those legs are paired appendages, and the developmental pathways for the leg on one side of the body are tied into the developmental pathways for the leg on the other side of the body, so it is <em>hard<\/em> to evolve an odd number of legs from these appendages.<\/p>\n\n<p>Hard is not the same as impossible, though. A comparable piece of evolution is the severe reduction in size of fins from one side of the body in flatfishes (flounders, sole, etc). I am struggling to think of terrestrial examples, but it is certainly evolutionarily possible to lose one appendage from a pair but keep the other.<\/p>\n","answer_id":39234,"question_id":39231,"up_vote_count":20,"last_edit_date":1444022630},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":11,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3baf199f552ba74762b32732e7fc5ba0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4419,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4419/quora-feans","reputation":173,"display_name":"Quora Feans","accept_rate":0},"score":2,"post_id":39235,"edited":false,"creation_date":1443895908,"comment_id":65621,"body":"-1 this does not answer the implicit question why are animals symmetrical."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":39235,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3baf199f552ba74762b32732e7fc5ba0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4419,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4419/quora-feans","reputation":173,"display_name":"Quora Feans","accept_rate":0},"edited":false,"creation_date":1443955928,"comment_id":65670,"body":"@QuoraFeans - How about now, see my edit showing embryonic development in bilateral symmetrical animalia"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jTz7e.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17086,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17086/chasly-from-uk","reputation":101,"display_name":"chasly from UK"},"score":0,"post_id":39235,"edited":false,"creation_date":1443994693,"comment_id":65692,"body":"Also it does not expla