nks for your critical reading. Done."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1444084131,"creation_date":1443868976,"body":"<p><strong>Short answer<\/strong><br>\nThe body plan of terrestrial organisms that feature limbs is typically bilaterally symmetric, and hence these organisms have an even number of appendages. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Background<\/strong><br>\nTerrestrial animals featuring appendices for motility (legs, arms) are typically <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_of_biological_complexity\">higher organisms<\/a>. Typically, the <strong><a href=\"http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/id.951,y.0,no.,content.true,page.3,css.print/issue.aspx\">body plan<\/a><\/strong> of higher animals such as us mammals is typically bilaterally symmetric (Fig. 1). Lower animals may be radially symmetric (e.g. round worms, jelly fish and star fish). Only the simplest of animlad have an asymmetric body plan, such as sponges. With a symmetrical body plan comes an even number of appendages. <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/joTCg.gif\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/joTCg.gif\" alt=\"symmetry\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Fig. 1. Different body plans. Source: <a href=\"http://www2.estrellamountain.edu/faculty/farabee/Biobk/BioBookDiversity_7.html\">Estrella Mountain Community College<\/a>.<\/sup>  <\/p>\n\n<p>The symmetrical body plan is already defined in the <a href=\"https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Blastocyst_Development\">blastocyst<\/a> stage during development. The blastocyst in humans forms in the first two weeks after gestation and contains 10 to 20 cells only (Fig. 2). <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/riiSj.jpg\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/riiSj.jpg\" alt=\"blastocyst\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Fig. 2. Human blastocyst at day 5. Source: <a href=\"https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Blastocyst_Development\">University of NSW<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n\n<p>While the blastocyst is not more than a globular clump of cells, it has two well-defined poles and a well-defined axis. In fact, it is thought that the single-celled zygote already has a well-defioned axis as it is has been shown that surviving <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_body\">polar bodies<\/a> during <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10008/\">oogenesis<\/a> (the formation of egg cells in the ovaria) have well-defined highly non-random positions in the zygote (Fig. 3.). These findings show that the single-celled zygote in bilateral symmetrical animals may already be defined at a single-celled stage <a href=\"http://dev.biologists.org/content/124/2/289.long\">(Gardner, 1997)<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Z8ECv.png\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Z8ECv.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Fig. 3. Blastocyst bilateral symmetry based on a mouse model. Source: <a href=\"http://dev.biologists.org/content/124/2/289.long\">(Gardner, 1997)<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>Reference<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://dev.biologists.org/content/124/2/289.long\">Gardner, <em>Development<\/em> (1997); <strong>124<\/strong>(2): 289-301<\/a><\/sub>   <\/p>\n","answer_id":39235,"question_id":39231,"up_vote_count":12,"last_edit_date":1444084131},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/32a68930c4349d18e5921d2ecedffa57?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19157,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19157/stephan-branczyk","reputation":139,"display_name":"Stephan Branczyk"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jTz7e.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17086,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17086/chasly-from-uk","reputation":101,"display_name":"chasly from UK"},"score":1,"post_id":39256,"edited":false,"creation_date":1444001278,"comment_id":65703,"body":"What about the Haggis? <a href=\"http://www.maths.ed.ac.uk/~jcollins/Haggis.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">maths.ed.ac.uk/~jcollins/Haggis.pdf<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":39256,"edited":false,"creation_date":1444064495,"comment_id":65754,"body":"Not all animals are symmetrical. Look at the adult flounder, for example."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/32a68930c4349d18e5921d2ecedffa57?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19157,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19157/stephan-branczyk","reputation":139,"display_name":"Stephan Branczyk"},"score":0,"post_id":39256,"edited":false,"creation_date":1444075404,"comment_id":65761,"body":"I didn&#39;t say they were. This is what I said:  &quot;It would make sense that a fish tail evolved and grew an internal muscle symmetry that allows it to eventually maintain a straight line. [...] Also, its muscle structure would need to be symmetrical between the left and the right side, so as not bias one side over the other.&quot; The flounder is also a perfect example of this. Its tail has a left-to-right symmetry."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1444000692,"creation_date":1443925394,"body":"<p>Imagine if the tail of a fish did behave like a leg (imagine a one legged frog). One side, either the left side or the right side, of that tail would naturally dominate and the fish would end up swimming naturally in circles.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Now assuming that being able to go in a straight line over longer distances is a small evolutionary advantage.<\/strong> It would make sense that that a fish tail evolved and grew an internal muscle symmetry that allows it to eventually maintain a straight line. <\/p>\n\n<p>The same goes if you were to grow a third leg tomorrow. In order for that third leg to be useful to you in evolutionary terms, it would have to be placed in such a way that it doesn't interfere with your balance and your maximum propulsion. Also, its muscle structure would need to be symmetrical between the left and the right side, so as not bias one side over the other. <\/p>\n\n<p>And of course, such a third leg wouldn't behave like the two other legs because of its forced internal symmetry, so we humans wouldn't call it a leg, we'd most likely call it a tail instead (a cat tail, a kangaroo tail, a snake tail, a fish tail, etc.)<\/p>\n\n<p>Now let's take a star fish with five \"leg-like\" appendages (although, that number can vary depending on the kind of star fish). Does my reasoning work with that kind of star fish also? The internal muscle structure of those five appendages are internally symmetrical, just like tails would be, not legs. Also, take a look at how a star fish moves. The propulsion doesn't come from its five appendages. Those five appendages help more with its balance and its positioning. And the propulsion actually comes from its many little tube legs at the bottom of those five appendages. So I'd say \"no\", a star fish is an interesting example, but it doesn't just have only five legs. <\/p>\n","answer_id":39256,"question_id":39231,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1444000692},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1443953520,"creation_date":1443953190,"body":"<p>The other part of the question has already been amply answered, so I will concentrate on the part of the question which asks about \"doesn't divide into odd numbers\"<\/p>\n\n<p>The assumption that organisms must have even numbers of cells merely because cells divide into two each time is false. For example, the nematode <em>Caenorhabditis elegans<\/em> has <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caenorhabditis_elegans#Notable_findings\">either 959 or 1031 cells<\/a> depending on its sex. Cells can be lost due to apoptosis or natural wear and tear. <\/p>\n\n<p>Even if that was not the case, cells divide at different rates and times, so it is perfectly plausible for an organism to have an odd number of cells. For example, when one of two cells divide, and the other does not, the final result would be 3 total cells, which is an odd number. <\/p>\n","answer_id":39265,"question_id":39231,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1443953520},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b9b2dcceda3b5751de782977d5965353?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19174,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19174/r-hess","reputation":111,"display_name":"R. Hess"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1443993244,"creation_date":1443993244,"body":"<p>The reason 'there are no known animals with an odd number of legs' - if that is indeed the case, given that stating a negative truth of high probability requires a great deal of examination of facts and records! - could be because it was a stage of development of organisms of a pre-Cambrian period stage of development, or at latest Early Cambrian.<\/p>\n\n<p>What I am thinking of specifically is the 'Ediacaran' organism/fossil named Charnia.  It shows 'glide reflection' in its development and organization, in which successive branches are opposite to the previous branch and a little further along the body axis.<\/p>\n\n<p>Charnia was, of course, a frond-like animal, resembling nothing relatively modern so much as a fern (which is a plant of course).  Given that it was an animal not a plant, and a very early animal for certain, it did not have opposite symmetry and thus, if it had evolved directly into a perambulating organism with legs, it might have had an odd number of them.<\/p>\n\n<p>When thinking of the conformation of animal life, it is as well to keep the Burgess Shale fossils in mind:  animal life that long ago, would appear to have been somewhat 'experimental' still (or, in a phase where all the basic problems were being worked out), and many differing types, some nowadays unrepresented, occurred, outre' in appearance, such as Hallucigenia and Opabinia.<\/p>\n\n<p>So to sum up, though I cannot point out a known and discovered odd-legged animal (in natural form, as opposed to through amputation or loss of limbs), it is quite possible there was such an animal in Cambrian or pre-Cambrian times, whose fossil remains are as yet undiscovered or not-yet-clearly-interpreted.<\/p>\n\n<p>Citations:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charnia\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charnia<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://paleobiology.si.edu/burgess/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://paleobiology.si.edu/burgess/<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":39278,"question_id":39231,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39231/why-are-there-no-known-animals-with-an-odd-number-of-legs","last_activity_date":1450106390,"creation_date":1443861638,"answer_count":5,"title":"Why are there no known animals with an odd number of legs?","body":"<p>In my 6<sup>th<\/sup> grade science book it is said that there are no three legged animals, and that no animal with an odd number of limbs exists. I checked <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tripedalism\">Wikipedia<\/a> and could confirm this: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>There are no known naturally occurring three-legged animals <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>On <a href=\"https://answers.yahoo.com/question/index?qid=20080324155204AAWxn85\">yahoo<\/a> it is said that <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>When an embryo is developing, it grows by cell division - the first single cell divides into two, then four, then eight etc. It doesnt' divide into odd numbers - each cell divides in half. So, this means that every creature develops the same on each side of it's body - same number of limbs per side.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>It seems to be a valid explanation. So is it true that any organ in any living organism is either one in amount or is in even number? And the explanation of yahoo.com is fine?<\/p>\n\n<p>I am a beginner in Biology. Please explain in simple terms.<\/p>\n","question_id":39231,"tags":["cell-biology","zoology","anatomy"],"score":21,"down_vote_count":0,"protected_date":1450107233,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3789,"up_vote_count":21,"last_edit_date":1443877332},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"score":0,"post_id":41505,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450108555,"comment_id":70449,"body":"I almost wonder if this isn&#39;t a typo for &#39;singular&#39;. I have no idea but I am curious."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41505,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450115952,"comment_id":70451,"body":"@Resonating I do 