per module, e.g.:<\/p>\n  \n  <p>BEGIN { $ENV{CLUSTALDIR} = '/home/username/clustalw1.8/' }\n  use Bio::Tools::Run::Alignment::Clustalw;<\/p><\/li>\n  <\/ol>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Unless you are doing massive amounts of sequence alignment, the <a href=\"http://www.ebi.ac.uk/Tools/msa/clustalw2/\" rel=\"nofollow\">clustalW2 webserver<\/a> is quicker, more sensitive and way easier to use.<\/p>\n","answer_id":28404,"question_id":28395,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1450082189},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2529c7a350c7665df3acdcd073f75167?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13093,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13093/steve-bond","reputation":324,"display_name":"Steve Bond"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1423330983,"creation_date":1423330983,"body":"<p>Based on the edit you made to your op, the dots are present in your initial stockholm alignment, and are simply being copied into the new clustal output. <\/p>\n\n<p>What is the source of your alignment to begin with? I'm assuming you're selecting individual rows from a larger alignment, given the odd distribution of gaps. This could give you a clue as to the actual significance of the dots (dashes are pretty much always gaps).<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, just fyi, if you want a command line tool to do the conversion for you, I have a python3 module called <a href=\"https://github.com/biologyguy/BuddySuite\" rel=\"nofollow\">SeqBuddy<\/a> that will work just fine. You'll need BioPython as a dependency though.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$: python3 SeqBuddy.py input.stockholm -sf clustal &gt; output.clustal\n<\/code><\/pre>\n","answer_id":28410,"question_id":28395,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/28395/what-is-the-meaning-of-dots-and-dashes-in-clustalw","last_activity_date":1450082189,"creation_date":1423285279,"answer_count":2,"title":"What is the meaning of dots and dashes in clustalw?","body":"<p>I am converting outputs in stockholm format to clustalw using <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Bio::AlignIO-&gt;new(-file =&gt; \"$ARGV[0]\", -format =&gt; \"stockholm\"); and\n\nBio::AlignIO -&gt;new (-format =&gt;'clustalw');\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I am also using <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>my $new=$aln-&gt;remove_columns(['all_gaps_columns'],'.');\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and got an output like<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>head1  ----------------.GG-.-gggaguggugugguuacgaaugUGGCCUCUGC-----A\n\nhead2  GGGGGUGUAGCUCAGU.GGU.A......................GAGCGGAUGCUUUGCA\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>What is the meaning of dots and dashes? Is this natural in a clustalw output? Am I getting a bug?<\/p>\n\n<p>I was unable to find the sequences I used in the original message but these two pose a similar pattern. These are RNA sequences, including pseudogenes, so there are lots of palindromic sequences.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code># STOCKHOLM 1.0\n#=GF AU Infernal 1.1.1\n\nhead1          --------UGGAGAAU.G--.-ugggcguc.gaucccacUUCCUCUCGCAUGCUAA..............................................................GCGAGC-gcucuaccacuugagcuaauucccc-..-------------..................................\n #=GR head1 PP ........89999988.4....6789****.********999**************..............................................................******.7999999866665555555554444..................................................\n\n head2         --------UGGAGAAU.---.-gcgggcaucgaucccgcUUCCUCUCGCAUGCUAA..............................................................GCGAGCG.........................-..-------------cucuaccauu........................\n #=GR head2  PP ........89999887......46789************9999*************..............................................................*****86.........................................4555666666........................\n\n\n CLUSTAL W (1.81) multiple sequence alignment\n\n head1  --------UGGAGAAU.G--.-ugggcguc.gaucccacUUCCUCUCGCAUGCUAA....\n head2  --------UGGAGAAU.---.-gcgggcaucgaucccgcUUCCUCUCGCAUGCUAA....\n<\/code><\/pre>\n","question_id":28395,"tags":["bioinformatics","sequence-alignment"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":525,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1423327390},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7bbc24925ff1139a376980af9bd8279d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17429,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17429/ahmed-abdullah","reputation":150,"display_name":"Ahmed Abdullah","accept_rate":38},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/UHqCr.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20472,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20472/duxan","reputation":121,"display_name":"duxan"},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449586573,"creation_date":1449586573,"body":"<p>According to <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/BLAST/tutorial/#head5\">BLAST documentation<\/a> statistics of local sequence alignment, when doing database searches, is done<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>by treating the database as a single long sequence of length N.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>N is therefore a sum of all sequences with varying sizes from a given database.<\/p>\n\n<p>Underlying assumption is that <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>query is <em>a priori<\/em> more likely to be related to a long than to a short sequence, because long sequences are often composed of multiple distinct domains.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>To calculate the probability, we need to choose a scoring scheme (for ungapped example: choose a mismatch penalties), which for a query sequence gives us a statistically significance score $S$. Expected number of alignments with score of at least $S$ follows Gumbel extreme value distribution:<\/p>\n\n<p>$$\nE = Kmn\\cdot e^{-\\lambda S}\n$$<\/p>\n\n<p>where <em>m<\/em> is query length, $n=N$ and $K$ and $\\lambda$ are distribution params.<\/p>\n\n<p>Again, according to <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/BLAST/tutorial/#head4\">docs<\/a> and its references, probability of finding at least one such seq would be $P=1-e^{-E_{(N)}}$, where $E_{(N)}$ is E-number for concatenated N-sequence and query sequence. <\/p>\n","answer_id":41330,"question_id":41190,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41190/how-is-the-probability-of-a-sequence-occuring-with-blast-calculated","last_activity_date":1450078978,"creation_date":1449140173,"answer_count":1,"title":"How is the probability of a sequence occuring with BLAST calculated?","body":"<p>What is the probability that a given nucleotide/amino acid sequence will occur in the whole database program BLAST searches in? How this probability is calculated? <\/p>\n","question_id":41190,"tags":["bioinformatics","homework","sequence-alignment"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":60,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1450078978},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/54a82fba3ce9f146c47e561b973f6adf?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5851,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5851/caters","reputation":341,"display_name":"Caters","accept_rate":36},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":2,"post_id":41500,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450052074,"comment_id":70398,"body":"Can you define &quot;sodium deficiency&quot;? Hyponatremia (not enough sodium in the blood) is usually not caused by insufficient sodium intake. If you eat, you&#39;ll get enough sodium."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41500,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i