or","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450068888,"creation_date":1450068888,"body":"<p>Another use of ATP is <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phosphorylation\" rel=\"nofollow\">phosphorylation<\/a> of different substrates including proteins. <\/p>\n","answer_id":41506,"question_id":41492,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41492/in-what-two-ways-is-atp-used-in-coupled-reactions","last_activity_date":1450068888,"creation_date":1450027095,"answer_count":2,"title":"In what two ways is ATP used in coupled reactions?","body":"<p>I already have down \"A coupled reaction is when leftover energy from a reaction fuels a reaction that needs more energy. ATP can break apart to transform into something new and use the energy created by breaking a bond to fuel a reaction in need of more energy\" I think that is one use but I am not sure and I still need another<\/p>\n","question_id":41492,"tags":["biochemistry","chemistry"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":56,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1450029282},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/DAX12.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4589,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4589/noumenon","reputation":113,"display_name":"Noumenon"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450068754,"creation_date":1450032587,"body":"<p>There are no epiphytic vines in the US. Most likely, if it's sturdy  enough that you can swing from it, it's the vine of a <a href=\"http://www.fcps.edu/islandcreekes/ecology/wild_grape.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">wild grape<\/a>. (The vine in the video is classic wild grape.)<\/p>\n\n<p>They grow like most other flowering plants: they start innocently enough with a seed that takes root in the ground. They are initially tender and small stemmed.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/bChMVm.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/bChMVm.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>From there, they grow along the ground, sending out tendrils. If they find something growing vertically, they cling to it (a shrub, tree trunk, or a low hanging branch) and grow upwards towards the light. If they have enough light (they are shade intolerant), they continue to grow, branch, and elongate. because they can become quite heavy, they break canopy branches of their supporting tree and fall in long loops toward the ground. <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/VuCCQm.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/VuCCQm.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>If the loop breaks for some reason, you have one swinging vine. But if you diligently follow it back, you'll find either the continuation of the vine near the canopy (the part after the break) or the trunk growing from the ground alongside of a nearby tree.<\/p>\n\n<p>Though cool-looking, they are very destructive, bringing down not only branches but often entire trees (plural. They intertwine different tree branches, and if they bring down one tree, others fall in a domino-effect.)<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/IDzWym.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/IDzWym.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Imagine that SOB hanging onto your upper arms for support (not the guy, the grapevine).<\/p>\n\n<p>Smaller vines (which can also be destructive) that climb up the sides of trees are Oriental Bittersweet, Poison Ivy, Virginia Creeper, etc. (Probably Kudzu as well, but we don't have that here yet.) But these aren't likely to become large or sturdy enough to swing from if they come loose from the tree.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/qzGPtm.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/qzGPtm.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>This is a photo of two common offenders: a wild grape (dark shreddy bark, about 2.5 inches in diameter) being slowly strangled by an oriental bittersweet (lighter bark), <em>both<\/em> climbing this large oak. If you look carefully, the base (roots) of both these vines are behind the tree (about five feet), one on either side. (You might have to take my word for it...)<\/p>\n\n<p><sub><a href=\"http://extension.psu.edu/natural-resources/forests/private/tools-resources/publications/invasive-plants-and-insects/wild-grape\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wild Grape<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":41494,"question_id":41479,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1450068754}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41479/what-is-the-lifecycle-of-hanging-woody-vines","last_activity_date":1450068754,"creation_date":1450007230,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the lifecycle of hanging woody vines?","body":"<p>In the first ten seconds of <a href=\"https://youtu.be/1GJj3sQZj9g\" rel=\"nofollow\">this video<\/a>, you can see a vine that appears to have started its life 60 feet up in a tree and has now grown down almost close enough to touch the ground. I have seen similar vines that do make it to the ground and start curling around, but don't sink roots. Why do they create this long woody stem? Or do they start at the bottom, grow up the tree, and then release their roots somehow so they can swing free? They're sometimes not wrapped around the trunk at all, just hanging from the very upper branches, as if their seeds found purchase there and started stealing nutrients to grow. Is that possible?<\/p>\n\n<p>I have swung from these in several locations in Wisconsin and Iowa. They're very tightly attached.<\/p>\n","question_id":41479,"tags":["botany"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":41494,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":70,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/275a855262518ede1c9ca4e435da5232?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20600,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20600/user20600","reputation":12,"display_name":"user20600"},"closed_date":1449995638,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SGxqm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18860,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18860/harry-vervet","reputation":1769,"display_name":"Harry Vervet"},"score":0,"post_id":41456,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449955354,"comment_id":70344,"body":"Yes, lysosomes (note spelling) exist. see <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lysosome\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lysosome<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":41456,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449963888,"comment_id":70356,"body":"The very first sentence of the Wikipedia article on lysosomes: <i>&quot;A lysosome (derived from the Greek words lysis, meaning &quot;to loosen&quot;, and soma, &quot;body&quot;) is a membrane-bound cell organelle found in most animal cells (they are absent in red blood cells).&quot;<\/i> So yes, any cell except RBCs would have lysosomes, as they are essential to the function of a metabolizing cell (which RBCs are not)."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/7QMwz.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20606,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20606/jason-yang","reputation":31,"display_name":"Jason Yang"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":1,"post_id":41472,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449984383,"comment_id":70363,"body":"Welcome, and thank you for your answer. You may want to consider an edit to provide some references to the information in your answer. It can help to provide the person who asked the question or others reading your answer who would like to research further a starting point."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41472,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450059824,"comment_id":70403,"body":"Thank you for the edit."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450059292,"creation_date":1449982822,"body":"<p>The function of a lysosome is to essentially digest and break down molecules (often compared to the stomach of the cell).<\/p>\n\n<p>For example, a cell with high proportions of lysosomes would be a macrophage, as its function is to neutralize pathogens. After the pathogen is engulfed by the macrophage, the vesicle formed, called a phagosome, fuses with a lysosome, and the lysosome's digestive enzymes work on breaking down the pathogen into harmless bits and pieces.<\/p>\n\n<p>In most cells, however, lysosomes also function to recycle the cell's own components, called autophagy. Damaged organelles are broken down by the lysosome and recycled.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>So, yes, there are many cells that do have lysosomes.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>The importance of the lysosome is shown when there is a malfunction in the lysosome. These diseases, called lysosomal storage diseases, occur when the lysosome does not function properly and the cell eventually is impaired by the buildup of a molecule that should have been broken down by the lysosome (e.g. Tay-Sachs disease).<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>References<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>The AP Biology textbook<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Campbell Biology 7th Edition, Chapter 6 - \"Lysosomes: Digestive Compartments\", although this is pretty much the same in any edition of this textbook<\/li>\n<li>Campbell Biology in Focus, Chapter 4 - \"Lysosomes: Digestive Compartments\"<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":41472,"question_id":41456,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1450059292}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41456/lysosome-function","last_activity_date":1450059292,"creation_date":1449942360,"answer_count":1,"title":"Lysosome function","body":"<p>Does any cell have lysosomes in it? Or maybe there are other organelles that do the same function. I read about it a lot and I can't find a good answer.<\/p>\n","question_id":41456,"tags":["cell-biology","organs"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":2,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":true,"view_count":44,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1449963679},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fc4e7dfc6752f72862ec6826a25d54fb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6158,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6158/user2373145","reputation":6,"display_name":"user2373145"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41501/yew-seed-dormancy-reduction","last_activity_date":1450051411,"creation_date":1450051411,"answer_count":0,"title":"Yew seed dormancy reduction","body":"<p>Yew seeds have very long dormancy when artificially planted.<br>\nThey are also adapted to passage through digestive systems of animals that eat/transport them.<\/p>\n\n<p>But could the dormancy be shorter (or the viability higher) if the seed passes through a birds digestive tract first? (An explanation: the seed's outer layers can get worn down that way, signalling that it is ready to start the process leading to germination.)<br>\nThat would imply that the dormancy could also be artificially shortened by eg. dipping the seeds in acid and then alkaline solutions, which would be great.<\/p>\n","question_id":41501,"tags":["biochemistry","molecular-biology","botany","seeds","germination"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":18,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/215351c880c211db9a5d0ca03ddc245a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":15946,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15946/benjli","reputation":119,"display_name":"Benjli","accept_rate":50},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":41493,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450032184,"comment_id":70384,"body":"Which city is it?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":41493,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450032214,"comment_id":70385,"body":"If you google the name of the place where this tree is found you might well found information."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/215351c880c211db9a5d0ca03ddc245a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":15946,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15946/benjli","reputation":119,"display_name":"Benjli","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":41493,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"crea