=\"http://bionumbers.hms.harvard.edu\" rel=\"nofollow\">Bionumbers<\/a>, the average transcription rate of RNA Polymerase II is about <a href=\"http://bionumbers.hms.harvard.edu/bionumber.aspx?&amp;id=105566\" rel=\"nofollow\">3.8 kb/min<\/a>. Other researchers measured it as <a href=\"http://bionumbers.hms.harvard.edu/bionumber.aspx?&amp;id=100661\" rel=\"nofollow\">6.3 nucleotides/sec<\/a>, or 378 bp/min, a 10-fold decrease. In the same paper, however, they measured the <em>maximum<\/em> rate at <a href=\"http://bionumbers.hms.harvard.edu/bionumber.aspx?&amp;id=100662\" rel=\"nofollow\">71.6 nucleotides/sec<\/a>, or 4.3 kb/min. To figure out the differences between the measurements, I suggest <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17676063\" rel=\"nofollow\">reading the paper<\/a>, but since it's from Nature Publishing Group you'll have to pay for it, unless you're at a subscribing university or institution (or someone posts the paper in the comments &lt;<em>hint hint<\/em>&gt;).<\/p>\n\n<p>So, the answer to your question, like most simple questions in biology, is <em>it depends<\/em>. It likely depends on the size of the gene, its structure, what transcription factors are necessary for the assembly of the polymerase complex, and, last but not least, exactly how and when you measure. Transcription likely initiates in fits and starts, then gets going faster. This is similar to (but not exactly like) measuring the speed of your car from Point A to Point B. Are you starting from a dead stop, or passing the starting marker at speed? Do you have to start the car first, or is it already running? How many turns and other slowdowns are on the road? Do you stop measuring as the car passes the finish marker, or when it comes to a complete stop? All of these things figure into the final answer, and the result given is entirely dependent on the scientists' choices of methodology.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you are interested in a broader discussion, I got started on <a href=\"http://book.bionumbers.org/what-is-faster-transcription-or-translation/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this page<\/a> at Bionumbers.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41434,"question_id":41431,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1450033364}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41431/time-needed-for-transcription-of-dna","last_activity_date":1450033364,"creation_date":1449858007,"answer_count":1,"title":"Time needed for transcription of DNA","body":"<p>How much time would it take to complete the transcription of an average-sized human gene?<\/p>\n","question_id":41431,"tags":["dna","transcription"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":2,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":true,"view_count":32,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1450033262},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/797af411d3d134ad312eebf5eeac0de5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20057/erlja-jkdf","reputation":16,"display_name":"Erlja Jkdf."},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/67f2ccd17aa6fd622152ad88fc2ae784?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14869,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14869/james-large","reputation":101,"display_name":"james large"},"score":0,"post_id":40649,"edited":false,"creation_date":1447615294,"comment_id":68550,"body":"Until a day comes when you can tell one dolphin what image to &quot;transmit&quot;, and then ask another what image it &quot;saw&quot;, it&#39;s pretty hard to imagine an experiment that would let you test that idea."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/67f2ccd17aa6fd622152ad88fc2ae784?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14869,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14869/james-large","reputation":101,"display_name":"james large"},"score":3,"post_id":40649,"edited":false,"creation_date":1447615485,"comment_id":68552,"body":"Humans can get <i>some<\/i> spatial information from the sounds that they hear.  Close your eyes, and listen to some good stereo mixes of music through headphones, and you will get a sense of a &quot;space&quot; around you with different instruments at different locations within that space.  Now try listening to the same mix in mono (or, with just one ear bud in place.)  All the spatial information is gone!  Whatever sounds one dolphin is able to make, it&#39;s still just <i>one<\/i> dolphin---just like one earbud..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/797af411d3d134ad312eebf5eeac0de5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20057/erlja-jkdf","reputation":16,"display_name":"Erlja Jkdf."},"score":0,"post_id":40649,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/67f2ccd17aa6fd622152ad88fc2ae784?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14869,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14869/james-large","reputation":101,"display_name":"james large"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1447615622,"comment_id":68553,"body":"Cheers, that makes sense."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":7,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":40674,"edited":false,"creation_date":1447684069,"comment_id":68645,"body":"+1 for a reasonable answer, but a human could draw a map of a dangerous area to warn later travellers. Assuming dolp