":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1278/ymar","reputation":262,"display_name":"ymar","accept_rate":75},"edited":false,"creation_date":1346079911,"comment_id":5018,"body":"@ymar No. They form an organism with their host cell. <i>Endosymbionts<\/i> are organisms but mitochondria are <i>derived<\/i> from endosymbionts. They are no longer endosymbionts (according to the common definition of the term)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/00bb55afe080d6ad677983ef7bd5286d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1278,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1278/ymar","reputation":262,"display_name":"ymar","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":3345,"edited":false,"creation_date":1346080313,"comment_id":5019,"body":"OK, I see. Could you explain what you mean by potential unbounded proliferation?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fdd630f72eef3790bfb4ef38d08c7f85?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/166/konrad-rudolph","reputation":3847,"display_name":"Konrad Rudolph"},"score":0,"post_id":3345,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/00bb55afe080d6ad677983ef7bd5286d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1278,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1278/ymar","reputation":262,"display_name":"ymar","accept_rate":75},"edited":false,"creation_date":1346081706,"comment_id":5022,"body":"@ymar Literally, proliferation without (theoretical) limit. Mitochondria can try as hard as they want, they cannot proliferate beyond their host cells. On the other hand, humans can theoretically proliferate to the bounds of the biosphere, which, itself, has no fixed bounds (except the edge of the Universe if you\u2019re so inclined)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/00bb55afe080d6ad677983ef7bd5286d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1278,"lin