e.\"<\/p>\n\n<p>Incidentally, I doubt that robins scan the ground for worms while in flight. They might search for suitable hunting grounds, but they search for prey on the ground.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41466,"question_id":41464,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1nMw6.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16866,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16866/theforestecologist","reputation":1908,"display_name":"theforestecologist","accept_rate":14},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449995230,"creation_date":1449983557,"body":"<p>So, we typically think about migrating birds as living somewhere (North) and then traveling South for the winter. This way of thinking is actually not accurate according to a number of ornithologists, including many I used to work with/for. Thy suggest that the birds <em>live<\/em> in the South and migrate North to breed and to avoid overcrowding of Southern locales. (Though see this <a href=\"https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn25996-flip-the-birds-migration-began-in-the-north-not-south/\" rel=\"nofollow\">article<\/a> that found support for the more often assumed N-to-S direction of migration). If 'South' is in fact their 'home,' then perhaps they will venture there regardless of weather patterns. However, perhaps neither of these thoughts applies to short-range migrators like robins. <\/p>\n\n<p>Also, many birds migrate during the dark hours of the night, so I wonder if the birds you saw were even migrating, per se, or just moving about regionally. <\/p>\n","answer_id":41474,"question_id":41464,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1449995230}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41464/large-congregation-of-birds","last_activity_date":1449995230,"creation_date":1449966242,"answer_count":2,"title":"Large congregation of birds?","body":"<p>This year in October I saw a lot of robins, male and female, finches and chickadees, and geese flying south.<\/p>\n\n<p>Surprisingly I didn't see many juveniles from previous broods. My guess is that juveniles are harder to see.<\/p>\n\n<p>And the robins were flying above me, looking for worms below me, and most ended up in tall shrubs. The finches stayed in place longer than the robins.<\/p>\n\n<p>So why this big congregation of birds when it is still going to be relatively warm for most of the fall(which it ended up being)?<\/p>\n\n<p>I live in ohio where it usually gets down to -4 in January and 90+ during the summer. <\/p>\n","question_id":41464,"tags":["ornithology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":41,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1449980814},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kpwGC.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6009,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6009/imprisoned-rhesus","reputation":250,"display_name":"Imprisoned Rhesus","accept_rate":75},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1nMw6.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16866,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16866/theforestecologist","reputation":1908,"display_name":"theforestecologist","accept_rate":14},"score":0,"post_id":41106,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449986362,"comment_id":70369,"body":"Do you have any close-up photos?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kpwGC.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6009,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6009/imprisoned-rhesus","reputation":250,"display_name":"Imprisoned Rhesus","accept_rate":75},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449990479,"creation_date":1449990479,"body":"<p>I eventually figured it out. It is the one-seed juniper, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juniperus_monosperma\" rel=\"nofollow\">Juniperus monosperma<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41476,"question_id":41106,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexch