:"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":3,"post_id":9098,"edited":false,"creation_date":1372948975,"comment_id":11818,"body":"Moreover, chlorophylls don&#39;t absorb all wavelengths equally. See <a href=\"http://www.botany.uwc.ac.za/ecotree/photosynthesis/spectrum.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1412867096,"creation_date":1372913264,"body":"<p>Yes, photosynthesis does occur on cloudy days where the light exposure is <em>diffuse<\/em> - but the overall picture is not as simple as your solar cell analogy.<\/p>\n\n<p>Consider one of the findings of the following article: \"<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1365-2435.2011.01934.x/abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\">Impact of clear and cloudy sky conditions on the vertical distribution of photosynthetic CO\u2082 uptake within a spruce canopy<\/a>\" (Urban et al. 2011), where one of the findings is that<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>that shoots from deep within the canopy contribute substantially to the overall carbon balance during cloudy days. But, although shade-adapted shoots had a markedly positive carbon balance over a 24-h period on cloudy days, their performance was impaired on sunny days contributing only a marginal or even negative carbon balance from the middle and shaded parts of the canopy.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>So, while leaves at the top of the canopy have a reduced rate of photosynthesis on cloudy days, leaves within the canopy and those that are shade-adapted, still photosynthesised.<\/p>\n\n<p>I hope this helps a bit.<\/p>\n","answer_id":9098,"question_id":9097,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1412867096}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9097/does-photosynthesis-occur-on-cloudy-days-or-does-it-require-direct-sunlight","last_activity_date":1449978903,"creation_date":1372909564,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does photosynthesis occur on cloudy days or does it require direct sunlight?","body":"<p>In my basic science classes in high school, I have learned that during photosynthesis, plants absorb sunlight and produce food by converting carbon dioxide and water into sugar and starch. <\/p>\n\n<p>To me, this seems similar to the analogy of solar cells that convert sunlight into electricity. When sunlight falls directly on the solar cell, it produces electricity, but even when it is cloudy with no direct sunlight available, electricity is produced, but with less efficiency. <\/p>\n\n<p>So can photosynthesis occur in plants only when they are in direct sunlight or does photosynthesis also occur during cloudy weather when the light is diffuse or indirect?<\/p>\n","question_id":9097,"tags":["photosynthesis","botany"],"score":7,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":4874,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1449978903},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f23444a71ffb8e6b5930b59e1eed15c3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5917,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5917/nerrolken","reputation":327,"display_name":"Nerrolken"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":21527,"edited":false,"creation_date":1411412551,"comment_id":33974,"body":"I don&#39;t know if this is related, but I&#39;ve done enough computer graphics programming to know that brown is hard color to reproduce on a computer. It&#39;s a mixture of red and green. If animals don&#39;t have good color vision, they might not be able to tell the difference between red and green, and it all looks brown anyway, kind of like colorblind men. However, I don&#39;t know how many animals have this issue, I think lack of blue vision is more common than lack or red or green."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":21527,"edited":false,"creation_date":1411424599,"comment_id":33980,"body":"i wonder if its because small mammals started out as terrestrial - bound to the ground where green is not as much a color.  certainly birds can be green when they need to be."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":1,"post_id":21527,"edited":false,"creation_date":1418167451,"comment_id":39815,"body":"But we clearly <i>need<\/i> it for the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green-beard_effect\" rel=\"nofollow\">Green-beard effect<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":10,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":21534,"edited":false,"creation_date":1411378955,"comment_id":33927,"body":"Whoever downvoted me, can you please explain why? If there is criticism on my answer, it will be helpful to know about it, so I can improve the answer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/oyQgf.jpg?s=128&g=1","user