er, liver and pancreas).<\/p>\n\n<p>You can find some more information <a href=\"https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003129.htm\">here<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.medicinenet.com/stool_color_changes/article.htm\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":37032,"question_id":37030,"up_vote_count":8}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37030/why-do-feces-vary-so-little-in-color","last_activity_date":1449808476,"creation_date":1440128317,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do feces vary so little in color?","body":"<p>Why do feces vary in color so much less than the food they are results of? E.g. you may eat food of all kinds of different colors but the resulting feces will almost always be some shade of brown.<\/p>\n","question_id":37030,"tags":["digestion","scatology"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":37032,"down_vote_count":2,"is_answered":true,"view_count":61,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1449808476}]}